{
  "texts": [
    "Some accounts emphasise the rational choice of endorsing the opinions of 'cue-givers', while others diagnose a mere 'contagion effect', i.e., an automatic response to the political stimuli of seeing a candidate's name becoming prominent in the media, or a bandwagon effect, i.e., the tendency to seek the gratification of cheering for the winning candidate.",
    "Specifically, an attractive theory of momentum highlights the internal deliberation triggered upon learning what others think (Mutz 1997).",
    "Using an experimental design, Mutz demonstrates that 'consensus cues', in the shape of 'information about mass support of candidates', have the beneficial effect of prompting voters who are moderately involved in the political process to rehearse arguments pro and against a popular candidate.",
    "In other words, learning about public opinions makes voters think critically.",
    "This, in turn, is likely to trigger an attitudinal shift favourable to said opinions."
  ]
}